00:25:27,720 --> 00:25:29,879
when they're always
comparing you to somebody else.

498
00:25:29,880 --> 00:25:32,599
Yeah. Right.

499
00:25:32,600 --> 00:25:34,079
I mean, I left home

500
00:25:34,080 --> 00:25:36,759
because I had parents
who didn't appreciate who I was.

501
00:25:36,760 --> 00:25:39,439
So why would I want to be
with new parents

502
00:25:39,440 --> 00:25:42,119
who could only appreciate me
if I was someone else?

503
00:25:42,120 --> 00:25:44,646
You might be
onto something there, son.

504
00:25:46,360 --> 00:25:49,359
You know, down here in these parts
we got a saying -

505
00:25:49,360 --> 00:25:53,719
“Sometimes when
you're panning for gold,

506
00:25:53,720 --> 00:25:56,610
"“you gotta try more than one stream."

507
00:26:02,320 --> 00:26:04,039
We really wish you'd reconsider.

508
00:26:04,040 --> 00:26:07,159
I'm sorry, but it
wouldn't be fair to any of us.

509
00:26:07,160 --> 00:26:09,199
Well, thanks for the opportunity, North.

510
00:26:09,200 --> 00:26:12,199
Oh, sir?
Yes, North'?

511
00:26:12,200 --> 00:26:16,439
(Sighs) I think it's only right
that I give you back the Astros.

512
00:26:16,440 --> 00:26:20,239
Well, thanks, son. That's a class gesture.

513
00:26:20,240 --> 00:26:23,279
Well... goodbye.

514
00:26:23,280 --> 00:26:25,719
So long, pard.
We'll miss you.

515
00:26:25,720 --> 00:26:27,210
Hold on there, son.

516
00:26:38,120 --> 00:26:41,079
Just a little something to remember
your old buddy Gabby by.

517
00:26:41,080 --> 00:26:43,159
Hope it brings you good luck.

518
00:26:43,160 --> 00:26:44,924
Thanks!

519
00:26:48,200 --> 00:26:50,089
<i>So North resumed his search.</i>

520
00:26:51,200 --> 00:26:53,599
<i>And though
he got to the airport by noon,</i>

521
00:26:53,600 --> 00:26:56,919
<i>out of respect for Ma and Pa Tex,
in true cowboy tradition,</i>

522
00:26:56,920 --> 00:27:00,679
<i>he chose to wait eight hours
so he could fly off into the sunset...</i>

523
00:27:00,680 --> 00:27:04,039
<i>"with no knowledge at all
of what was going on back home."</i>

524
00:27:04,040 --> 00:27:06,999
BOY: How much longer do we
have to put with this indignity?

525
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:10,119
How much longer
must we tolerate these injustices?

526
00:27:10,120 --> 00:27:12,679
The subservience!
KIDS: Yeah!

527
00:27:12,680 --> 00:27:15,439
It's humiliating, my friends.
It's demeaning.

528
00:27:15,440 --> 00:27:18,519
Right on!
Now is the time to say no!

529
00:27:18,520 --> 00:27:20,399
Now is the time to say,

530
00:27:20,400 --> 00:27:24,079
“Just because you were born
25 or 30 years before me

531
00:27:24,080 --> 00:27:27,279
“doesn't make you smart,
it doesn't make you right...

532
00:27:27,280 --> 00:27:29,199
"“..it just makes you OLD!"

533
00:27:29,200 --> 00:27:31,959
(All cheer)

534
00:27:31,960 --> 00:27:35,239
It just makes you
smell worse in the morning!

535
00:27:35,240 --> 00:27:37,879
(All cheer)

536
00:27:37,880 --> 00:27:39,959
Now is the time to band together

537
00:27:39,960 --> 00:27:43,719
and let our parents know
that we're at the dawn of a new era -

538
00:27:43,720 --> 00:27:46,079
the era of our liberation!

539
00:27:46,080 --> 00:27:48,559
(All applaud loudly)

540
00:27:48,560 --> 00:27:51,359
An era made possible by a kid

541
00:27:51,360 --> 00:27:55,046
who had the guts to fight
for the power we now possess!

542
00:27:57,960 --> 00:28:01,359
And now the man
whose brilliant legal mind

543
00:28:01,360 --> 00:28:03,559
shone the light
on the pathway to freedom -

544
00:28:03,560 --> 00:28:07,359
Mr Arthur Ulysses Belt Esquire!

545
00:28:07,360 --> 00:28:10,364
(All cheer loudly)

546
00:28:12,520 --> 00:28:14,319
Thank you.

547
00:28:14,320 --> 00:28:18,039
I am but a humble servant,
standing at your ready,

548
00:28:18,040 --> 00:28:21,119
<i>to assist in this noble cause!</i>

549
00:28:21,120 --> 00:28:22,599
Viva el Norte!

550
00:28:22,600 --> 00:28:25,843
ALL: Viva el Norte!

551
00:28:29,880 --> 00:28:32,879
<i>But like I said,
North didn't know about any of this.</i>

552
00:28:32,880 --> 00:28:34,839
<i>He was on his way to Hawaii,</i>

553
00:28:34,840 --> 00:28:38,039
<i>to meet what he hoped would be
his brand-new parents.</i>

554
00:28:38,040 --> 00:28:41,044
(HAWAIIAN MUSIC)

555
00:28:54,440 --> 00:28:56,039
Governor and Mrs Ho'?

556
00:28:56,040 --> 00:28:58,359
Aloha, North.

557
00:28:58,360 --> 00:29:00,319
Welcome to our island paradise, North.

558
00:29:00,320 --> 00:29:01,879
Aloha.

559
00:29:01,880 --> 00:29:04,079
We got a big day planned for you.

560
00:29:04,080 --> 00:29:06,048
Waki-Waki will take you to the house,
to change.

561
00:29:06,080 --> 00:29:07,199
OK.

562
00:29:07,200 --> 00:29:08,519
Aloha!

563
00:29:08,520 --> 00:29:11,039
'Aloha'?
I thought that meant 'hello'!

564
00:29:11,040 --> 00:29:14,439
Ah, in Hawaii,
'aloha' means 'hello' AND 'goodbye'.

565
00:29:14,440 --> 00:29:16,319
Doesn't that get confusing?

566
00:29:16,320 --> 00:29:18,359
Only when you're firing someone.

567
00:29:18,360 --> 00:29:20,647
Oh. Well, aloha!

568
00:29:22,560 --> 00:29:24,439
Isn't he great?

569
00:29:24,440 --> 00:29:26,966
(RELAXING HAWAIIAN MUSIC)

570
00:29:33,680 --> 00:29:35,559
You know, North, if you settled here,

571
00:29:35,560 --> 00:29:38,799
you'd be many years younger because
of the difference in time zones.

572
00:29:38,800 --> 00:29:40,279
Which means you won't die

573
00:29:40,280 --> 00:29:43,239
as early as you would
if you lived on the mainland.

574
00:29:43,240 --> 00:29:44,730
That's a plus!

575
00:29:50,760 --> 00:29:52,239
Another thing, North -

576
00:29:52,240 --> 00:29:55,519
living in Hawaii, it's much easier
to get into a good college.

577
00:29:55,520 --> 00:29:56,999
How's that'?

578
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:00,239
Here in the islands, we have
only 12 letters in our alphabet.

579
00:30:00,240 --> 00:30:01,719
Really?
That's right.

580
00:30:01,720 --> 00:30:03,879
Five vowels.
W, .E, , T, .0,' .U, _

581
00:30:03,880 --> 00:30:07,199
Seven consonants.
H, ' .K, I, ' M, ' N, ' p, ' .W, _

582
00:30:07,200 --> 00:30:08,759
Well, I didn't know that.

583
00:30:08,760 --> 00:30:10,839
Well, sure! Just think about it.

584
00:30:10,840 --> 00:30:14,079
'Waikiki' 'Honolulu'...
'Kona Pali', 'Mauna Lani'...

585
00:30:14,080 --> 00:30:15,679
Well, that's very interesting,

586
00:30:15,680 --> 00:30:18,119
but how does that
help me get into college?

587
00:30:18,120 --> 00:30:21,359
Well, since we don't use
the letters 'B', 'C', 'D' and 'F',

588
00:30:21,360 --> 00:30:23,567
you're pretty much guaranteed
to get straight 'A's.

589
00:30:31,280 --> 00:30:35,679
What do you think?
Well, I like what I see.

590
00:30:35,680 --> 00:30:39,730
But I do have one question,
just for my own peace of mind.

591
00:30:40,720 --> 00:30:42,199
What is it?

592
00:30:42,200 --> 00:30:44,559
Well, I hope I'm not being insensitive,
but...

593
00:30:44,560 --> 00:30:48,359
you wouldn't have a dead kid
whose shoes you want me to fill, right?

594
00:30:48,360 --> 00:30:49,839
Dead kid'?

595
00:30:49,840 --> 00:30:54,159
North, Hawaii is a lush and fertile land.

596
00:30:54,160 --> 00:30:58,359
In fact, there's only one
barren area on all of our islands.

597
00:30:58,360 --> 00:31:01,204
Unfortunately, it's Mrs Ho.

598
00:31:02,240 --> 00:31:07,087
But if all goes right,
you will be our first child.

599
00:31:09,280 --> 00:31:11,965
Wow. What a great day.

600
00:31:13,160 --> 00:31:15,559
You know, this might really work out.

601
00:31:15,560 --> 00:31:19,359
As far as I'm concerned, there's just
a few minor details to discuss.

602
00:31:19,360 --> 00:31:23,559
You know, bedtimes, sleep-overs, your
views on snacks - that sort of thing.

603
00:31:23,560 --> 00:31:26,159
Well, what are we standing here for'?

604
00:31:26,160 --> 00:31:28,919
Let's go inside
and push a few numbers around, huh?

605
00:31:28,920 --> 00:31:30,604
See what we come up with.

606
00:31:32,320 --> 00:31:35,324
(FAST-PACED TRIBAL MUSIC)

607
00:31:41,760 --> 00:31:44,839
<i>ANNOUNGER'. Ladies and gentlemen,
Governor and Mrs Ho.</i>

608
00:31:44,840 --> 00:31:47,844
(All cheer)

609
00:31:49,200 --> 00:31:52,204
(Speaks Hawaiian)

610
00:31:54,360 --> 00:31:57,319
Ladies and gentlemen,
fellow 50th-Staters,

611
00:31:57,320 --> 00:31:59,639
I am thrilled to announce

612
00:31:59,640 --> 00:32:02,039
that we have reached
an agreement in principle

613
00:32:02,040 --> 00:32:04,199
which allows me
to introduce to you today

614
00:32:04,200 --> 00:32:06,359
a young man who in the coming years

615
00:32:06,360 --> 00:32:09,519
will be to Hawaii
what the peach is to Georgia,

616
00:32:09,520 --> 00:32:13,999
what the apple is to New York,
and what the wind is to Chicago.

617
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:19,000
Now, without further ado, please
give a big, warm Hawaiian welcome

618
00:32:19,120 --> 00:32:23,919
to our new pride and joy -
our son, North!

619
00:32:23,920 --> 00:32:26,571
(All cheer)

620
00:32:28,840 --> 00:32:32,003
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

621
00:32:48,160 --> 00:32:51,642
(All cheer)

622
00:32:56,720 --> 00:32:58,199
What is that'?

623
00:32:58,200 --> 00:33:01,199
Son, that'll be in every airport,
along every highway...

624
00:33:01,200 --> 00:33:04,199
My crack?! My crack is gonna
be shown in every airport?!

625
00:33:04,200 --> 00:33:05,679
Now, son...

626
00:33:05,680 --> 00:33:08,919
What gives you the right
to show my crack on every highway?

627
00:33:08,920 --> 00:33:10,399
See, the truth is, North,

628
00:33:10,400 --> 00:33:14,199
I'm the Governor of a state
that's running a little low on self-esteem.

629
00:33:14,200 --> 00:33:15,839
After 35 years of statehood,

630
00:33:15,840 --> 00:33:18,799
people still don't treat Hawaii
like we're part of the country.

631
00:33:18,800 --> 00:33:20,679
Sure, there's a star on the flag,

632
00:33:20,680 --> 00:33:23,359
but why didn't anyone show up
during Hands Across America?

633
00:33:23,360 --> 00:33:27,119
We waited for days, and not even
a call to say nobody was coming.

634
00:33:27,120 --> 00:33:29,559
It's just plain inconsiderate.
He's right.

635
00:33:29,560 --> 00:33:31,959
People from the mainland
just don't care about Hawaii.

636
00:33:31,960 --> 00:33:34,919
They come here with their knobby knees
and their pale kids,

637
00:33:34,920 --> 00:33:37,319
and they eat our food
and watch our whales

638
00:33:37,320 --> 00:33:39,479
and say 'Aloha!', like they really mean it.

639
00:33:39,480 --> 00:33:43,759
7-10 days later they drop us like
a sack of rancid poi and go home!

640
00:33:43,760 --> 00:33:45,959
And we're supposed to feel good
about ourselves?

641
00:33:45,960 --> 00:33:49,199
Excuse me, but what does this
have to do with my crack?!

642
00:33:49,200 --> 00:33:52,919
Oh, don't you see, North,
if you lived here in Hawaii,

643
00:33:52,920 --> 00:33:55,719
people would be
more inclined to settle here.

644
00:33:55,720 --> 00:33:58,839
So they can be close to my CRACK?!

645
00:33:58,840 --> 00:34:02,999
North, North... you're
very important to us.

646
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:07,369
I don't know.
I need some time to think, OK'?

647
00:34:11,240 --> 00:34:13,159
One, two, three, fourjacks!

648
00:34:13,160 --> 00:34:16,359
Come on, guys, don't just stand
there. Get your body in motion!

649
00:34:16,360 --> 00:34:19,519
You might just like it.
And squat down, hup, and...

650
00:34:19,520 --> 00:34:24,159
Now, what is the point'?
Gabby?! What are you doing here?

651
00:34:24,160 --> 00:34:27,959
They say for every hour you exercise
you add an hour to your life.

652
00:34:27,960 --> 00:34:29,599
Who needs all that extra time

653
00:34:29,600 --> 00:34:31,479
if you're just gonna spend it exercising?

654
00:34:31,480 --> 00:34:33,639
You see where I'm going
with this, Junior?

655
00:34:33,640 --> 00:34:36,319
Who's Gabby?
He's a ranch hand from Texas.

656
00:34:36,320 --> 00:34:38,129
Not familiar with the gentleman.

657
00:34:39,160 --> 00:34:42,839
So, how's it feel
to be Hawaii's new first son?

658
00:34:42,840 --> 00:34:45,799
Well, I'm not so sure
that's what I want to be.

659
00:34:45,800 --> 00:34:50,039
Why not? Beautiful climate.
Can't beat the fashion.

660
00:34:50,040 --> 00:34:54,039
Yeah, I know, but I don't think
I should settle for parents

661
00:34:54,040 --> 00:34:56,999
who have to show
my most private crevice on a billboard

662
00:34:57,000 --> 00:34:59,239
to make them feel better
about themselves!

663
00:34:59,240 --> 00:35:00,959
It's refreshing to meet a kid

664
00:35:00,960 --> 00:35:03,119
who has such strong convictions
about his crack.

665
00:35:03,120 --> 00:35:05,691
( METAL DETECTOR BUZZES )
Whoa! Whoa!

666
00:35:08,040 --> 00:35:09,519
(Sighs)

667
00:35:09,520 --> 00:35:12,959
Dig, man -
the way I always figure this deal is,

668
00:35:12,960 --> 00:35:16,159
it's the parents who are
supposed to make the kids feel better,

669
00:35:16,160 --> 00:35:17,679
not the other way around.

670
00:35:17,680 --> 00:35:19,479
Yeah.

671
00:35:19,480 --> 00:35:22,529
Hang in there, kid.
You'll find what you're looking for.

672
00:35:23,720 --> 00:35:25,609
I hope so.

673
00:35:27,440 --> 00:35:30,119
<i>Although he came up short
in both Texas and Hawaii,</i>

674
00:35:30,120 --> 00:35:31,599
<i>North felt no anxiety,</i>

675
00:35:31,600 --> 00:35:34,604
<i>as he still had eight weeks
till his Labor Day deadline.</i>

676
00:35:36,600 --> 00:35:38,079
<i>PILOT: Welcome to Juneau, Alaska.</i>

677
00:35:38,080 --> 00:35:39,559
<i>Please remain seated</i>

678
00:35:39,560 --> 00:35:42,519
<i>until the plane comes to a
complete stop in Anchorage, Alaska.</i>

679
00:35:42,520 --> 00:35:43,999
<i>To accompany our skid,</i>

680
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:47,119
<i>we will be showing you
another full-length feature film.</i>

681
00:35:47,120 --> 00:35:52,120
Our friend had a dream,
and that dream is becoming a reality.

682
00:35:52,400 --> 00:35:55,359
<i>Meanwhile, as North
was skidding his way to Anchorage,</i>

683
00:35:55,360 --> 00:35:56,959
<i>things were heating up at home.</i>

684
00:35:56,960 --> 00:35:59,719
<i>Winchell's inspirational speeches
had created a groundswell.</i>

685
00:35:59,720 --> 00:36:01,519
<i>And all across the land,</i>

686
00:36:01,520 --> 00:36:04,490
<i>kids were continuing to hold
their parents at emotional gunpoint.</i>

687
00:36:05,480 --> 00:36:07,479
Anything else, son?
Yes.

688
00:36:07,480 --> 00:36:11,041
How's my room coming along?
I'll have it spotless by dinner.

689
00:36:12,040 --> 00:36:14,679
Viva el Norte.

690
00:36:14,680 --> 00:36:16,359
And as of next Monday,

691
00:36:16,360 --> 00:36:19,319
no parent will be permitted to see
an R-rated movie

692
00:36:19,320 --> 00:36:21,639
unless accompanied by a kid.

693
00:36:21,640 --> 00:36:23,119
Yeah, right.

694
00:36:23,120 --> 00:36:26,319
Arthur, do I detect a note of melancholy?

695
00:36:26,320 --> 00:36:29,199
It's just that North
still hasn't found new parents.

696
00:36:29,200 --> 00:36:30,679
Maybe he never will.

697
00:36:30,680 --> 00:36:33,919
Maybe this free agency thing
will just blow up in our face!

698
00:36:33,920 --> 00:36:35,559
I'm surprised at you, Arthur.

699
00:36:35,560 --> 00:36:39,079
Do you think I would actually embark
on an endeavour of this magnitude

700
00:36:39,080 --> 00:36:40,599
without a contingency plan?

701
00:36:40,600 --> 00:36:44,279
Contingency plan?
Oh, good. I love those.

702
00:36:44,280 --> 00:36:45,919
One Coca-Cola.
Right here.

703
00:36:45,920 --> 00:36:48,239
And one Sex on the Beach.

704
00:36:48,240 --> 00:36:50,766
Aren't I naughty?

705
00:36:51,760 --> 00:36:54,719
To our future.
And what a future it is!

706
00:36:54,720 --> 00:36:58,079
According to the latest polls,
parents are so nervous

707
00:36:58,080 --> 00:37:02,679
that 78% of them say they will vote
however their kids tell them to.

708
00:37:02,680 --> 00:37:06,605
And since those kids will do
whatever YOU tell them to...

709
00:37:07,680 --> 00:37:09,170
well, I, ah...

710
00:37:10,760 --> 00:37:14,439
(Chuckles) What I mean is...
That's right.

711
00:37:14,440 --> 00:37:17,439
I'm lying here with the next
President of the United States.

712
00:37:17,440 --> 00:37:20,439
(Laughs gleefully)

713
00:37:20,440 --> 00:37:22,319
I'm happy for you, Arthur.

714
00:37:22,320 --> 00:37:25,079
I'm sure you'll make a FINE
commander-in-chief.

715
00:37:25,080 --> 00:37:28,319
Hey, dollface, could you
concentrate on my lower back?

716
00:37:28,320 --> 00:37:29,970
It's where my tension builds up.

717
00:37:35,320 --> 00:37:37,719
<i>ANNOUNGER'. Flight 24 from Hawaii
by way of Juneau</i>

718
00:37:37,720 --> 00:37:39,370
is now arriving at Gate 7.

719
00:37:40,360 --> 00:37:42,727
<i>CONTROLLER'.
Pressure 119-91, 11 feet.</i>

720
00:37:47,880 --> 00:37:50,079
STEWARDESS: Bye-bye.
Hey, great landing, guys.

721
00:37:50,080 --> 00:37:52,759
You really got that skid thing
down to a science.

722
00:37:52,760 --> 00:37:54,359
Thanks for the kind words, North.

723
00:37:54,360 --> 00:37:56,239
Not saying we haven't dented terminals
occasionally,

724
00:37:56,240 --> 00:37:58,919
but after a while, you get the hang of it.

725
00:37:58,920 --> 00:38:00,649
Thanks.
(All laugh)

726
00:38:01,640 --> 00:38:04,199
<i>North's first impression of Alaska
was a positive one.</i>

727
00:38:04,200 --> 00:38:07,359
<i>The air was clean,
it was breathtakingly beautiful</i>

728
00:38:07,360 --> 00:38:10,679
<i>and best of all, it was far away
from everyone and everything.</i>

729
00:38:10,680 --> 00:38:12,879
<i>So there was nothing
to distract these people</i>

730
00:38:12,880 --> 00:38:15,279
<i>from concentrating on
life's most precious commodity -</i>

731
00:38:15,280 --> 00:38:17,119
<i>the love of a good family.</i>

732
00:38:17,120 --> 00:38:20,119
(Huskies bark)

733
00:38:20,120 --> 00:38:23,124
(BUSY MUSIC)

734
00:38:27,360 --> 00:38:28,850
Whoa, whoa!

735
00:38:45,400 --> 00:38:48,919
Here you go, North -
a nice cup of hot cocoa.

736
00:38:48,920 --> 00:38:53,119
And to go with that,
our State dish - Eskimo pie.

737
00:38:53,120 --> 00:38:54,610
Thank you.

738
00:38:58,280 --> 00:39:01,079
Well, hey, what do you know'?
The salmon are running.

739
00:39:01,080 --> 00:39:04,559
I'm gonna get a couple of poles
and go fishing with my boy.

740
00:39:04,560 --> 00:39:06,050
Great! I love fishing.

741
00:39:07,440 --> 00:39:09,359
OK.

742
00:39:09,360 --> 00:39:11,559
(FISHING POLES ENTER HOLE)

743
00:39:11,560 --> 00:39:14,564
(Whistles merrily)

744
00:39:16,880 --> 00:39:19,884
(Both whistle)

745
00:39:21,480 --> 00:39:23,369
(Whistles)

746
00:39:28,280 --> 00:39:30,079
(All whistle)

747
00:39:30,080 --> 00:39:32,519
Ah, this is the life. Right, son?
Sure is.

748
00:39:32,520 --> 00:39:34,519
Do you like Christmas, North'?
Who doesn't'?

749
00:39:34,520 --> 00:39:37,479
You've never had a Christmas
till you've had an Alaskan Christmas.

750
00:39:37,480 --> 00:39:40,159
Right - since our days
last for months at a time,

751
00:39:40,160 --> 00:39:41,799
you can just imagine the festivities!

752
00:39:41,800 --> 00:39:46,199
Why, opening the presents
takes three weeks alone, right, Ma'?

753
00:39:46,200 --> 00:39:49,439
Oh, this all sounds great,
but what's the catch'?

754
00:39:49,440 --> 00:39:51,159
Well, what do you mean?

755
00:39:51,160 --> 00:39:53,049
I mean, what's in it for you?

756
00:39:55,080 --> 00:39:57,559
Nothing-Really?

757
00:39:57,560 --> 00:40:02,560
No dead kids? No low self-esteem?
No frozen skeletons in your closet?

758
00:40:03,280 --> 00:40:06,359
(Both laugh)

759
00:40:06,360 --> 00:40:09,639
We have pride, North.
And we're proud of our pride.

760
00:40:09,640 --> 00:40:11,679
We wouldn't ask anything of a child.

761
00:40:11,680 --> 00:40:15,719
We want you to follow your dreams
and be the best North you can be.

762
00:40:15,720 --> 00:40:19,599
We know you'll be a source of great
pride to the entire Eskimo community

763
00:40:19,600 --> 00:40:21,284
for many, many years to come.

764
00:40:22,280 --> 00:40:23,759
(Chuckles)

765
00:40:23,760 --> 00:40:26,923
Oh, jeepers creepers!
That reminds me.

766
00:40:28,120 --> 00:40:32,039
Oh, Dad, let's go! Time to flow.
OLD MAN: Coming!

767
00:40:32,040 --> 00:40:35,567
Time to what?!
OK, buckle up! It's a long walk.

768
00:40:38,240 --> 00:40:42,639
Who's that'?
North, this is your new grandfather.

769
00:40:42,640 --> 00:40:44,439
Hello, North.

770
00:40:44,440 --> 00:40:47,799
Hello. What do you mean,
it's time to flow'?

771
00:40:47,800 --> 00:40:51,399
Well, when an Eskimo gets too old
or weak to contribute to society,

772
00:40:51,400 --> 00:40:54,519
the whole family gets together
and everybody walks to the ocean.

773
00:40:54,520 --> 00:40:55,999
That's right.

774
00:40:56,000 --> 00:40:59,239
Then the revered old Eskimo
is proudly placed on an ice floe

775
00:40:59,240 --> 00:41:02,239
and sent out to sea,
so he can die, with dignity.

776
00:41:02,240 --> 00:41:05,039
And pride.
Alright, everybody. Let's go.

777
00:41:05,040 --> 00:41:06,519
But, wait a minute!

778
00:41:06,520 --> 00:41:09,759
Just because he's old doesn't mean
he can't belong to the family.

779
00:41:09,760 --> 00:41:11,239
Well, it's our tradition.

780
00:41:11,240 --> 00:41:14,479
I promise you, North, Grandpa wants this
just as much as anyone.

781
00:41:14,480 --> 00:41:15,959
Right, Grandpa?

782
00:41:15,960 --> 00:41:19,043
Yeah, right. I... I've been
looking forward to this.

783
00:41:22,360 --> 00:41:25,039
<i>As the family
made their long trek to the sea,</i>

784
00:41:25,040 --> 00:41:27,999
<i>North took the opportunity
to get close to his new grandpa,</i>

785
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:31,239
<i>which was easy since he had
a tremendous affection for old folks.</i>

786
00:41:31,240 --> 00:41:33,639
<i>He found them to be warm,
understanding,</i>

787
00:41:33,640 --> 00:41:36,405
<i>and most importantly,
way too tired to yell.</i>

788
00:41:37,800 --> 00:41:41,279
<i>Knowing that his time with Grandpa
was limited, North tried to take in</i>

789
00:41:41,280 --> 00:41:44,799
<i>all this wise old man had to offer
about life in the tundra.</i>

790
00:41:44,800 --> 00:41:46,279
And another thing.

791
00:41:46,280 --> 00:41:48,399
Up here, if your mother <i>says,</i>

792
00:41:48,400 --> 00:41:51,479
“Don't make a face because it could
freeze in that position",

793
00:41:51,480 --> 00:41:54,119
you better take her seriously.

794
00:41:54,120 --> 00:41:57,039
Jeez. Can't you
hang around a little longer?

795
00:41:57,040 --> 00:42:00,159
There's so much you can teach me.
( BUZZ! )

796
00:42:00,160 --> 00:42:02,879
Next!
ALL: Goodbye.

797
00:42:02,880 --> 00:42:05,599
Yeah, yeah. OK, OK, OK.
Goodbye, goodbye. C'mon, let's go.

798
00:42:05,600 --> 00:42:07,999
Only got four months of sunlight here.
Move it!

799
00:42:08,000 --> 00:42:09,519
Next! Come on, let's go.

800
00:42:09,520 --> 00:42:12,919
(Presses buzzer) Come on! Come on!
Should've done this before.

801
00:42:12,920 --> 00:42:16,399
I got a civilisation to run here.
Can you move it along, please?

802
00:42:16,400 --> 00:42:18,479
<i>Thank you.
(Presses buzzer) Next! Let's go.</i>

803
00:42:18,480 --> 00:42:21,051
Don't act like you don't know
what's going on.

804
00:42:22,040 --> 00:42:25,639
Well, goodbye, North.

805
00:42:25,640 --> 00:42:29,519
Are you sure you have to go?
Oh, don't worry about him, North.

806
00:42:29,520 --> 00:42:32,479
He's had a great life,
and he's happy to set sail...

807
00:42:32,480 --> 00:42:33,959
before he starts
embarrassing himself.

808
00:42:33,960 --> 00:42:37,479
Take it from us, North - when drool
hardens, it's not a pretty sight.

809
00:42:37,480 --> 00:42:39,199
"But...
“But, but, but..." Come on!

810
00:42:39,200 --> 00:42:42,159
Let's go, pal. You know
where you're going. Take a walk.

811
00:42:42,160 --> 00:42:44,039
Come on, move it along. Let's go!

812
00:42:44,040 --> 00:42:46,999
Yeah, bye-bye-bye. Fine. Thank you.
Goodbye, Dad!

813
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:49,162
BYE, Dad!
(Sadw) 'Bye.

814
00:42:50,600 --> 00:42:55,199
Listen, if there's a change in policy
in the next couple of weeks,

815
00:42:55,200 --> 00:42:57,679
feel free to track me down.

816
00:42:57,680 --> 00:42:59,319
What did he say?
Hey!

817
00:42:59,320 --> 00:43:02,961
What do you say we grab a ride home?
That's a great idea!

818
00:43:05,520 --> 00:43:08,364
(ATMOSPHERIC MUSIC)

819
00:43:11,720 --> 00:43:13,919
Oh, North. Don't worry about Grandpa.

820
00:43:13,920 --> 00:43:16,048
He'll be OK.
Yeah.

821
00:43:17,520 --> 00:43:20,490
Can I ride on top?
Why, sure. It's the best view.

822
00:43:22,520 --> 00:43:25,519
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

823
00:43:25,520 --> 00:43:28,330
Landscape sure is beautiful up here.

824
00:43:30,560 --> 00:43:32,759
Hey! It's you.

825
00:43:32,760 --> 00:43:34,999
No, it's not.

826
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:36,490
Oh.

827
00:43:39,040 --> 00:43:41,646
(Breathes in and out)
Smell that fresh air.

828
00:43:42,640 --> 00:43:44,119
No smog up here.

829
00:43:44,120 --> 00:43:46,559
How could they do that'?

830
00:43:46,560 --> 00:43:50,319
Not even my original parents
would send my grandpa away like that.

831
00:43:50,320 --> 00:43:52,999
Hey, son! How's the view up there?

832
00:43:53,000 --> 00:43:56,079
Great. Thanks.

833
00:43:56,080 --> 00:43:57,799
(Softly) 'Son'.

834
00:43:57,800 --> 00:44:00,199
You know, I don't want
to overstep my bounds,

835
00:44:00,200 --> 00:44:02,359
but unless I'm mistaken,
you're that fella North.

836
00:44:02,360 --> 00:44:05,599
And unless I'm further mistaken,
you have a deadline of Labor Day,

837
00:44:05,600 --> 00:44:08,279
which is a week from tomorrow,
to choose new parents.

838
00:44:08,280 --> 00:44:10,039
And unless I'm mistaken even further,

839
00:44:10,040 --> 00:44:12,239
you still haven't found
what you're looking for.

840
00:44:12,240 --> 00:44:15,199
How could Labor Day be next week'?
I just got here!

841
00:44:15,200 --> 00:44:18,199
You walked from your house to
the ice floes, right? Yeah.

842
00:44:18,200 --> 00:44:20,879
A seven-week walk,
even with the wind behind you.

843
00:44:20,880 --> 00:44:24,119
No wonder
we stopped for lunch 49 times!

844
00:44:24,120 --> 00:44:25,599
Ah, don't feel bad.

845
00:44:25,600 --> 00:44:28,559
It's that six months of daylight thing.
It throws everybody off.

846
00:44:28,560 --> 00:44:31,519
I myself only showered 12 times
during the '70s.

847
00:44:31,520 --> 00:44:35,399
Oh, man. I'll never find new parents.

848
00:44:35,400 --> 00:44:36,879
Unless I misinterpret the ruling,

849
00:44:36,880 --> 00:44:39,319
you can always go back
to your original parents.

850
00:44:39,320 --> 00:44:41,759
Oh, yeah.
That's just what I want to do.

851
00:44:41,760 --> 00:44:45,839
Return to the people who haven't even
tried to contact me in over 8 weeks!

852
00:44:45,840 --> 00:44:49,359
Take me to the airport!
There's lots to do and not much time.

853
00:44:49,360 --> 00:44:50,964
You got it. Hyah!

854
00:44:52,440 --> 00:44:55,039
<i>So a now desperate North,
with time running out,</i>

855
00:44:55,040 --> 00:44:56,759
<i>raced towards an uncertain future.</i>

856
00:44:56,760 --> 00:45:00,119
<i>Understandably, he was upset his parents
hadn't called in two months.</i>

857
00:45:00,120 --> 00:45:01,599
<i>What he couldn't know, however,</i>

858
00:45:01,600 --> 00:45:04,559
<i>was his parents hadn't
done much of anything in two months.</i>

859
00:45:04,560 --> 00:45:07,039
As curator
of the Smithsonian Institution,

860
00:45:07,040 --> 00:45:10,319
it is my distinct honor
to unveil the newest addition

861
00:45:10,320 --> 00:45:12,839
to our illustrious
Hall of Achievement.

862
00:45:12,840 --> 00:45:16,159
At 78 consecutive days and counting,

863
00:45:16,160 --> 00:45:19,039
the longest simultaneous coma
in medical history -

864
00:45:19,040 --> 00:45:21,691
ladies and gentlemen, North's folks.

865
00:45:23,320 --> 00:45:25,759
(All murmur)

866
00:45:25,760 --> 00:45:28,239
I'll now take questions.
Yes.

867
00:45:28,240 --> 00:45:32,439
How can you equate a medical oddity
with man's landing on the moon?

868
00:45:32,440 --> 00:45:36,759
With all due respect to the
achievements of the 'Apollo 11' crew,

869
00:45:36,760 --> 00:45:40,279
the sociological impact
of what these folks did

870
00:45:40,280 --> 00:45:43,879
dwarfs those of Mr Armstrong et al.

871
00:45:43,880 --> 00:45:45,519
But all they did was faint.

872
00:45:45,520 --> 00:45:46,999
And, in so doing,

873
00:45:47,000 --> 00:45:50,759
shifted the familial bounds of power
throughout the world.

874
00:45:50,760 --> 00:45:54,839
“Throughout the world"? This thing
is getting bigger than we thought.

875
00:45:54,840 --> 00:45:59,359
Bigger than YOU thought. That's why
you're only gonna be President.

876
00:45:59,360 --> 00:46:02,999
Continuing process of new status...

877
00:46:03,000 --> 00:46:04,599
Wait. I just thought of something.

878
00:46:04,600 --> 00:46:06,999
What if they awaken
in the next eight days,

879
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:09,159
begging and pleading
for North to come back?

880
00:46:09,160 --> 00:46:12,130
Oh, my God!
What if North goes back to his FOLKS?!

881
00:46:13,120 --> 00:46:17,519
Arthur. Don't you know
that that's an impossibility?

882
00:46:17,520 --> 00:46:20,559
That I would use all of my power

883
00:46:20,560 --> 00:46:23,159
to prevent a thing like that
from happening?

884
00:46:23,160 --> 00:46:26,519
Oh. OK.

885
00:46:26,520 --> 00:46:28,759
What do you say
we grab some Chinese?

886
00:46:28,760 --> 00:46:31,047
Maybe the MSG will calm you down.

887
00:46:33,360 --> 00:46:36,039
<i>Despite North's concern
about his approaching deadline,</i>

888
00:46:36,040 --> 00:46:38,159
<i>he did take solace in the fact</i>

889
00:46:38,160 --> 00:46:41,519
<i>that the Lord needed only six days
to create the entire universe.</i>

890
00:46:41,520 --> 00:46:44,359
<i>Certainly a kid of his calibre,
given two extra days,</i>

891
00:46:44,360 --> 00:46:46,727
<i>should be able to find
two measly parents.</i>

892
00:46:54,280 --> 00:46:57,679
Greetings, North.

893
00:46:57,680 --> 00:46:59,599
I'm thy new father.

894
00:46:59,600 --> 00:47:02,479
And this good woman,
who art my wife,

895
00:47:02,480 --> 00:47:04,209
art thy new mother.

896
00:47:05,240 --> 00:47:09,564
And these art thy new brothers
who art named Ezekiel.

897
00:47:10,960 --> 00:47:14,851
And these art thy new brothers
who art named Art.

898
00:47:16,720 --> 00:47:19,239
Hey! Hey, this looks great!

899
00:47:19,240 --> 00:47:21,559
I have always dreamt of a life

900
00:47:21,560 --> 00:47:23,519
without the ever-present nuisance
of electricity.

901
00:47:23,520 --> 00:47:26,519
Uh... uh... just let me grab something
from the plane.

902
00:47:26,520 --> 00:47:30,319
I seem to have left my butter churn
in the overhead compartment. (Laughs)

903
00:47:30,320 --> 00:47:31,810
(Yells) FLOOR IT!

904
00:47:34,560 --> 00:47:37,639
<i>While it was not
like North to make snap judgments,</i>

905
00:47:37,640 --> 00:47:39,319
<i>there were only seven days left.</i>

906
00:47:39,320 --> 00:47:42,479
<i>He had a world full of potential
parents to evaluate.</i>

907
00:47:42,480 --> 00:47:44,199
(GONG CLASHES LOUDLY)

908
00:47:44,200 --> 00:47:47,204
(People chant obediently)

909
00:47:49,080 --> 00:47:52,039
MAN: Long live the North Dynasty!

910
00:47:52,040 --> 00:47:55,519
(People respond)

911
00:47:55,520 --> 00:47:57,279
Give him the emperor cut!

912
00:47:57,280 --> 00:47:59,931
(GONG RESOUNDS)

913
00:48:07,200 --> 00:48:08,679
(AFRICAN TRIBAL MUSIC)

914
00:48:08,680 --> 00:48:11,439
( MAN YELLS LIKE TARZAN )

915
00:48:11,440 --> 00:48:12,930
(Speaks tribal language)

916
00:48:31,280 --> 00:48:33,439
You seem like very nice folks.

917
00:48:33,440 --> 00:48:35,759
But to be totally honest with you,

918
00:48:35,760 --> 00:48:39,367
if I lived here, I'm not sure
I'd get much homework done.

919
00:48:43,440 --> 00:48:46,319
(CANCAN MUSIC
PLAYS BRIGHTLY)

920
00:48:46,320 --> 00:48:48,322
(Man and woman laugh)

921
00:48:52,000 --> 00:48:55,359
(Dogs bark wildly)

922
00:48:55,360 --> 00:48:56,850
(Laughs) (Laughs)

923
00:48:57,840 --> 00:48:59,359
Quiet, Harry! Quiet.

924
00:48:59,360 --> 00:49:01,639
I think he's trying
to tell us something.

925
00:49:01,640 --> 00:49:04,479
(Mumbles and grunts
unintelligibly)

926
00:49:04,480 --> 00:49:07,119
(Sings)
♪ Whack, whack, whack-a-doo! ♪

927
00:49:07,120 --> 00:49:09,399
(Laughs like rooster)

928
00:49:09,400 --> 00:49:10,879
(Man grunts like horse)

929
00:49:10,880 --> 00:49:12,879
(Woman hums)

930
00:49:12,880 --> 00:49:14,609
WOMAN: Oh, my Catholic God!

931
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:20,799
<i>With three days to go before
his 12:00 noon Labor Day deadline,</i>

932
00:49:20,800 --> 00:49:24,159
<i>North, the little world traveller,
arrived in New York today</i>

933
00:49:24,160 --> 00:49:26,559
<i>to interview his final set of parents -</i>

934
00:49:26,560 --> 00:49:28,559
<i>Ward and Donna Nelson,</i>

935
00:49:28,560 --> 00:49:31,279
<i>who, along with their two children
Bud and Laura,</i>

936
00:49:31,280 --> 00:49:34,279
<i>live in the quaint upstate town
of Bedford.</i>

937
00:49:34,280 --> 00:49:37,079
<i>When contacted earlier at his office,</i>

938
00:49:37,080 --> 00:49:39,479
<i>Ward, the local paediatrician -</i>

939
00:49:39,480 --> 00:49:41,759
<i>who, we understand,
still makes house calls, said,</i>

940
00:49:41,760 --> 00:49:44,439
<i>“My family and I
would like nothing better</i>

941
00:49:44,440 --> 00:49:48,159
<i>“than to see North's long journey
finally be rewarded</i>

942
00:49:48,160 --> 00:49:50,159
<i>“with a warm and loving home,</i>

943
00:49:50,160 --> 00:49:52,679
<i>“and we hope
we can provide it for him.”</i>

944
00:49:52,680 --> 00:49:54,319
(UPLIFTING MUSIC)

945
00:49:54,320 --> 00:49:55,810
Thanks.

946
00:50:02,280 --> 00:50:05,679
Hi, North! Ward! Bud! Laura! He's here.

947
00:50:05,680 --> 00:50:07,159
He's here! (Chuckles)

948
00:50:07,160 --> 00:50:08,799
Hi, North.

949
00:50:08,800 --> 00:50:10,279
Hi!
Hello.

950
00:50:10,280 --> 00:50:12,519
Welcome to our home, son.
Come on in.

951
00:50:12,520 --> 00:50:15,039
Are you tired? Hungry?
Mum made chocolate-chip cookies.

952
00:50:15,040 --> 00:50:16,839
Do you like Nintendo?
Yeah.

953
00:50:16,840 --> 00:50:18,839
<i>REPORTER'. Today at Mount Rushmore</i>

954
00:50:18,840 --> 00:50:21,359
<i>thousands of angry parents gathered
to voice their opposition</i>

955
00:50:21,360 --> 00:50:24,439
<i>to the bill that would lower
the voting age to seven.</i>

956
00:50:24,440 --> 00:50:28,399
<i>According to Arthur Belt, the rising
politician who drafted the bill...</i>

957
00:50:28,400 --> 00:50:30,799
Oh, wait.
They were talking about me.

958
00:50:30,800 --> 00:50:32,279
Relax, Arthur.

959
00:50:32,280 --> 00:50:36,119
Soon you'll hear your name so much,
even you'll be sick of it.

960
00:50:36,120 --> 00:50:38,999
I highly doubt it.

961
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:40,479
(PHONE RINGS)

962
00:50:40,480 --> 00:50:42,199
Talk to me.

963
00:50:42,200 --> 00:50:44,719
It's Al with the sleeping dogs.

964
00:50:44,720 --> 00:50:46,439
Yeah? What about 'em'?

965
00:50:46,440 --> 00:50:48,886
Looks like they counted
their last sheep.

966
00:50:50,400 --> 00:50:52,679
So it does.

967
00:50:52,680 --> 00:50:55,839
How long will it take
to get Operation Xerox into place?

968
00:50:55,840 --> 00:50:58,839
Less than a minute, boss.
Go to it. Al'?

969
00:50:58,840 --> 00:51:00,319
<i>Yeah, boss'?</i>

970
00:51:00,320 --> 00:51:03,279
Don't be surprised if there's
extra zeros in your next pay.

971
00:51:03,280 --> 00:51:05,559
Thanks, boss. I appreciate it.
And Al'?

972
00:51:05,560 --> 00:51:08,439
Yeah, boss?
Don't be surprised if there isn't.

973
00:51:08,440 --> 00:51:09,930
I understand.

974
00:51:12,480 --> 00:51:15,086
(Both yawn and groan)

975
00:51:24,480 --> 00:51:27,559
Good morning!
Where are we'?

976
00:51:27,560 --> 00:51:29,359
Oh! Where's our son?

977
00:51:29,360 --> 00:51:32,679
Oh. Can we see our son?
Absolutely. Just follow me.

978
00:51:32,680 --> 00:51:36,399
We've got a limo waiting
with coffee and some nice, hot Danish.

979
00:51:36,400 --> 00:51:37,959
Oh, that sounds good.

980
00:51:37,960 --> 00:51:40,639
I seem to have worked up an appetite.

981
00:51:40,640 --> 00:51:42,279
Honey'?
I could eat.

982
00:51:42,280 --> 00:51:43,799
Right this way.

983
00:51:43,800 --> 00:51:46,804
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

984
00:52:01,360 --> 00:52:02,839
Hike!

985
00:52:02,840 --> 00:52:05,719
OK, Laura, sack the quarterback.
Come here! Hey!

986
00:52:05,720 --> 00:52:07,719
Oh!
BUD: Touchdown! Yeah!

987
00:52:07,720 --> 00:52:09,959
You faked me out of my socks, North.

988
00:52:09,960 --> 00:52:11,599
Come and get it!

989
00:52:11,600 --> 00:52:13,079
Oh, here we go.

990
00:52:13,080 --> 00:52:16,039
It's great having you here.
I've always wanted a brother.

991
00:52:16,040 --> 00:52:18,639
Now I have two big brothers!

992
00:52:18,640 --> 00:52:21,999
I know we're excited
to have North as part of our family,

993
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:25,079
but he hasn't decided
if he wants to stay with us.

994
00:52:25,080 --> 00:52:27,079
North, you've got to stay.
Yeah.

995
00:52:27,080 --> 00:52:29,079
DONNA: Help yourself, everybody. Dig in.

996
00:52:29,080 --> 00:52:31,879
Mum, can we go
to the carnival tomorrow'?

997
00:52:31,880 --> 00:52:34,319
Yeah! Can we'?
I don't see why not.

998
00:52:34,320 --> 00:52:37,279
Ward?
Sounds good to me.

999
00:52:37,280 --> 00:52:40,079
North...

1000
00:52:40,080 --> 00:52:42,119
we miss you so much.

1001
00:52:42,120 --> 00:52:44,119
Please forgive us.

1002
00:52:44,120 --> 00:52:47,319
We made... so many mistakes.

1003
00:52:47,320 --> 00:52:50,959
We... we should have appreciated you
more.

1004
00:52:50,960 --> 00:52:54,931
If only you could give us
just one more chance.

1005
00:52:56,000 --> 00:52:57,490
We love you, son.

1006
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:01,279
We love you very much.
(Sobs)

1007
00:53:01,280 --> 00:53:02,759
CUT!

1008
00:53:02,760 --> 00:53:04,879
Very nice! Very, very nice!

1009
00:53:04,880 --> 00:53:08,159
Touching! Moving!
And yet not over-the-top!

1010
00:53:08,160 --> 00:53:09,639
(Whispers) Keep it rolling.

1011
00:53:09,640 --> 00:53:11,679
So... crazy summer, huh?

1012
00:53:11,680 --> 00:53:14,199
Oh, terrible.
Very disturbing.

1013
00:53:14,200 --> 00:53:16,079
Look. I know what you're going through.

1014
00:53:16,080 --> 00:53:19,323
But even if North doesn't come back,
you can always adopt!

1015
00:53:20,440 --> 00:53:23,559
Just the other day I met this adorable
little boy, seven years old.

1016
00:53:23,560 --> 00:53:25,159
His name was Hugh.

1017
00:53:25,160 --> 00:53:28,562
Maybe you can adopt him.
Maybe Hugh can be your son.

1018
00:53:30,280 --> 00:53:31,919
We don't want Hugh.

1019
00:53:31,920 --> 00:53:33,799
He's NOT our son.

1020
00:53:33,800 --> 00:53:35,839
We want North.

1021
00:53:35,840 --> 00:53:39,319
I understand. It was insensitive
of me to even bring it up.

1022
00:53:39,320 --> 00:53:41,359
Uh... you folks want some more coffee?

1023
00:53:41,360 --> 00:53:44,239
Nah..that's OK.
Not for me.

1024
00:53:44,240 --> 00:53:47,799
I still don't understand why we can't
speak to North in person.

1025
00:53:47,800 --> 00:53:50,119
L...l think that would be a big mistake.

1026
00:53:50,120 --> 00:53:52,759
North is very angry right now.
He's very sensitive.

1027
00:53:52,760 --> 00:53:56,399
You show up unannounced -
this thing could blow up in your face!

1028
00:53:56,400 --> 00:53:59,359
It would kill me to see that happen.

1029
00:53:59,360 --> 00:54:02,359
So my suggestion is
you lay low for a while.

1030
00:54:02,360 --> 00:54:04,159
You'll be escorted to the plaza.

1031
00:54:04,160 --> 00:54:07,839
I told Jean-Pierre to give you
all the room service you want.

1032
00:54:07,840 --> 00:54:09,519
And, as North's best friend,

1033
00:54:09,520 --> 00:54:13,599
I'd be happy to show them this tape
to pave the way for you.

1034
00:54:13,600 --> 00:54:15,799
Oh!
Thank you, Winchell.

1035
00:54:15,800 --> 00:54:18,839
Oh, yes.
You're a real friend.

1036
00:54:18,840 --> 00:54:21,919
I do what I can.
Bring the car for North's folks.

1037
00:54:21,920 --> 00:54:23,599
Yes, sir. Consider it done.

1038
00:54:23,600 --> 00:54:27,159
You know... you're doing very well
for a sixth-grader.

1039
00:54:27,160 --> 00:54:28,839
Yeah... l got a few breaks.

1040
00:54:28,840 --> 00:54:30,319
How...'? I was wo...'?

1041
00:54:30,320 --> 00:54:33,642
Adam, take the tape down to editing.
(Sighs)

1042
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:38,679
LAURA: Colonel Mustard...
WARD: Yeah?

1043
00:54:38,680 --> 00:54:40,999
In the study with the rope?

1044
00:54:41,000 --> 00:54:43,519
I don't have any of those.
Neither do I.

1045
00:54:43,520 --> 00:54:46,519
BUD AND NORTH: Me either.
Let's see.

1046
00:54:46,520 --> 00:54:50,279
Colonel Mustard... in the study...
and here's the rope!

1047
00:54:50,280 --> 00:54:53,159
OTHERS: Alright!
WARD: Good job, kitten!

1048
00:54:53,160 --> 00:54:54,839
LAURA: Can we play again?

1049
00:54:54,840 --> 00:54:56,799
No, it's bedtime. Tomorrow's a big day.

1050
00:54:56,800 --> 00:54:59,479
You don't want to be tired
for the carnival.

1051
00:54:59,480 --> 00:55:01,799
Mum's right. It's bedtime right now.
OK.

1052
00:55:01,800 --> 00:55:03,319
Goodnight, Mum
Goodnight, honey.

1053
00:55:03,320 --> 00:55:06,399
Goodnight, North.
Goodnight, Mum. Goodnight, Dad.

1054
00:55:06,400 --> 00:55:08,679
Brush your teeth before you go to bed.

1055
00:55:08,680 --> 00:55:10,682
(DOORBELL RINGS)

1056
00:55:14,440 --> 00:55:18,479
Sorry to bother you so late. I've
got something for a kid named North.

1057
00:55:18,480 --> 00:55:19,959
What is it?

1058
00:55:19,960 --> 00:55:22,279
An urgent message
from his original parents.

1059
00:55:22,280 --> 00:55:25,011
I'll see that he gets it.
Thank you.

1060
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:32,239
North, honey'?
Yeah?

1061
00:55:32,240 --> 00:55:34,199
Can you come here for a minute?

1062
00:55:34,200 --> 00:55:35,690
Coming!

1063
00:55:37,040 --> 00:55:39,999
What is it'?
North, a man left this tape for you.

1064
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:42,162
He says it's a message
from your parents.

1065
00:55:43,280 --> 00:55:45,919
From my parents?
Do you mind if I...'?

1066
00:55:45,920 --> 00:55:47,649
Of course not.

1067
00:55:51,120 --> 00:55:53,079
Would you like to be alone, North'?

1068
00:55:53,080 --> 00:55:54,605
No, that's OK.

1069
00:56:04,920 --> 00:56:07,119
WOMAN ON VIDEO:
<i>After what you've been through,</i>

1070
00:56:07,120 --> 00:56:09,319
<i>what would you like to tell your son?</i>

1071
00:56:09,320 --> 00:56:10,799
<i>We don't want you.</i>

1072
00:56:10,800 --> 00:56:12,999
<i>How can you say that? He's your son.</i>

1073
00:56:13,000 --> 00:56:14,639
<i>He's not our son.</i>

1074
00:56:14,640 --> 00:56:18,319
<i>Aren't you bothered by the prospect
of never seeing your son again?</i>

1075
00:56:18,320 --> 00:56:20,239
<i>Nah. That's OK.</i>

1076
00:56:20,240 --> 00:56:24,079
<i>Isn't this a gut-wrenching,
torturous emotional experience?</i>

1077
00:56:24,080 --> 00:56:26,639
<i>Not for me.
He's not our son.</i>

1078
00:56:26,640 --> 00:56:28,319
<i>We don't want you.</i>

1079
00:56:28,320 --> 00:56:31,324
(MELANCHOLY MUSIC)

1080
00:56:35,200 --> 00:56:38,319
North, honey, are you OK'?

1081
00:56:38,320 --> 00:56:40,879
Is there anything we can do for you?

1082
00:56:40,880 --> 00:56:44,168
Yeah. Let me be your son.

1083
00:56:46,080 --> 00:56:47,839
<i>Finally North had new parents.</i>

1084
00:56:47,840 --> 00:56:51,359
<i>Parents who made him feel wanted,
secure and loved.</i>

1085
00:56:51,360 --> 00:56:54,319
<i>Yet something was still wrong.</i>

1086
00:56:54,320 --> 00:56:56,599
<i>The Nelsons
were everything he was looking for,</i>

1087
00:56:56,600 --> 00:56:58,204
<i>so why couldn't he embrace them?</i>

1088
00:56:59,200 --> 00:57:01,009
<i>North needed answers.</i>

1089
00:57:04,600 --> 00:57:06,599
(TRAIN HORN BLOWS)

1090
00:57:06,600 --> 00:57:09,319
North, we just don't understand
why you're leaving.

1091
00:57:09,320 --> 00:57:10,799
Neither do I.

1092
00:57:10,800 --> 00:57:14,799
You're all nice people.
I'm really gonna miss you.

1093
00:57:14,800 --> 00:57:16,879
But I've just got to be alone.

1094
00:57:16,880 --> 00:57:19,008
We're going to miss you too.

1095
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:21,923
And so will Oliver.

1096
00:57:23,880 --> 00:57:27,719
North'? Here.

1097
00:57:27,720 --> 00:57:30,679
In case you get hungry on your way
to New York.

1098
00:57:30,680 --> 00:57:32,279
Thanks, Mom.

1099
00:57:32,280 --> 00:57:34,567
I mean, Mrs Nelson.

1100
00:57:36,240 --> 00:57:37,719
'Bye.

1101
00:57:37,720 --> 00:57:40,724
(MELANCHOLY MUSIC)

1102
00:57:49,520 --> 00:57:52,559
<i>So, with just 24 hours
until his Labor Day deadline,</i>

1103
00:57:52,560 --> 00:57:56,039
<i>no hope of parents and the prospect
of living in an orphanage looming,</i>

1104
00:57:56,040 --> 00:57:58,799
<i>North felt he only had
one option left.</i>

1105
00:57:58,800 --> 00:58:00,450
<i>He would disappear.</i>

1106
00:58:08,040 --> 00:58:10,441
Can you spare some extra change?

1107
00:58:11,520 --> 00:58:13,010
Oh!

1108
00:58:18,120 --> 00:58:21,639
Here. Maybe it will bring you
more luck than it brought me.

1109
00:58:21,640 --> 00:58:24,879
Hey! It's got a hole in it!

1110
00:58:24,880 --> 00:58:27,199
What good does this do me?

1111
00:58:27,200 --> 00:58:29,519
<i>Yes, he would disappear.</i>

1112
00:58:29,520 --> 00:58:31,359
<i>And where better to do that</i>

1113
00:58:31,360 --> 00:58:35,239
<i>than amidst the teeming,
faceless masses of the naked city?</i>

1114
00:58:35,240 --> 00:58:38,239
(SEEDY MUSIC)

1115
00:58:38,240 --> 00:58:41,244
(STREET NOISES,
PEOPLE SHOUT)

1116
00:58:51,480 --> 00:58:53,369
Shut up!
I can arrest you both.

1117
00:59:06,800 --> 00:59:09,199
He's heading into the park.
Don't worry, boss.

1118
00:59:09,200 --> 00:59:11,719
I'm just looking for
the right time and place.

1119
00:59:11,720 --> 00:59:14,959
So long, Al.
What was that all about?

1120
00:59:14,960 --> 00:59:18,442
Well, it seems that our young friend
has had a change of heart.

1121
00:59:19,920 --> 00:59:21,399
Change of heart'?

1122
00:59:21,400 --> 00:59:22,879
He's left the Nelsons

1123
00:59:22,880 --> 00:59:25,599
and decided to grace our fair city
with his presence.

1124
00:59:25,600 --> 00:59:27,079
Oh, no!

1125
00:59:27,080 --> 00:59:29,279
Well, this ruins everything.

1126
00:59:29,280 --> 00:59:32,399
Arthur, please. Use your head.

1127
00:59:32,400 --> 00:59:34,519
This is a godsend.

1128
00:59:34,520 --> 00:59:36,479
It is'?
Of course.

1129
00:59:36,480 --> 00:59:40,359
As we speak,
grown-ups across this great land of ours

1130
00:59:40,360 --> 00:59:41,999
are feeling humiliated.

1131
00:59:42,000 --> 00:59:44,599
They blame North for all
their frustrations.

1132
00:59:44,600 --> 00:59:47,679
Do you realise how many
of those angry parents

1133
00:59:47,680 --> 00:59:51,159
would like nothing better than to do away
with our little friend?

1134
00:59:51,160 --> 00:59:53,679
And do you know the one catalyst

1135
00:59:53,680 --> 00:59:56,570
that can give a political movement
true cohesion?

1136
00:59:58,680 --> 01:00:01,719
That's right. A martyr.

1137
01:00:01,720 --> 01:00:07,363
You're a genius! I mean, it's brilliant.
It's absolutely Winchellian. It...

1138
01:00:09,360 --> 01:00:11,319
But for North to be a martyr,

1139
01:00:11,320 --> 01:00:14,119
doesn't he have to be killed
by an angry parent'?

1140
01:00:14,120 --> 01:00:17,679
Well, maybe we'll get lucky.

1141
01:00:17,680 --> 01:00:19,159
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1142
01:00:19,160 --> 01:00:20,759
(GUNSHOT)

1143
01:00:20,760 --> 01:00:23,759
<i>As North ran for his life
he couldn't help wondering</i>

1144
01:00:23,760 --> 01:00:26,999
<i>how a dream of finding the perfect
parents had become a nightmare.</i>

1145
01:00:27,000 --> 01:00:29,679
(GUNSHOTS)

1146
01:00:29,680 --> 01:00:32,684
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1147
01:00:33,920 --> 01:00:35,399
(Gasps for breath)

1148
01:00:35,400 --> 01:00:38,404
(CAROUSEL MUSIC)

1149
01:00:47,280 --> 01:00:48,770
(GUNSHOT)

1150
01:00:50,320 --> 01:00:51,810
Ah! Ah!

1151
01:00:54,360 --> 01:00:57,364
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1152
01:00:59,360 --> 01:01:01,919
(CAROUSEL MUSIC)

1153
01:01:01,920 --> 01:01:04,039
Damn it!

1154
01:01:04,040 --> 01:01:07,044
(FOREBODING MUSIC)

1155
01:01:46,240 --> 01:01:48,559
(MUSIC INTENSIFIES)

1156
01:01:48,560 --> 01:01:50,679
Psst! North, over here.

1157
01:01:50,680 --> 01:01:52,762
Adam! What are you doing here?

1158
01:01:55,040 --> 01:01:56,719
Listen to me very carefully.

1159
01:01:56,720 --> 01:01:58,679
I'm not here. You never saw me.

1160
01:01:58,680 --> 01:02:00,959
We're not even having this
conversation right now.

1161
01:02:00,960 --> 01:02:02,599
Got that'?
Got what?

1162
01:02:02,600 --> 01:02:04,079
Perfect.

1163
01:02:04,080 --> 01:02:06,162
So, what are we not talking about?

1164
01:02:07,280 --> 01:02:08,759
This.
What?

1165
01:02:08,760 --> 01:02:10,399
I don't see anything.
Exactly.

1166
01:02:10,400 --> 01:02:13,079
What you don't see is a tape
of the conversation

1167
01:02:13,080 --> 01:02:14,559
Winchell had with your parents.

1168
01:02:14,560 --> 01:02:16,439
I saw it.
No, you didn't.

1169
01:02:16,440 --> 01:02:18,399
Oh, I forgot. I didn't see it.

1170
01:02:18,400 --> 01:02:22,159
You did see it. This is what
you didn't see when you saw it.

1171
01:02:22,160 --> 01:02:24,599
I see.
I don't think you do.

1172
01:02:24,600 --> 01:02:26,199
Look at the tape.

1173
01:02:26,200 --> 01:02:28,159
So, how did you find me?

1174
01:02:28,160 --> 01:02:30,199
Winchell.
He bugged the Nelsons' phones.

1175
01:02:30,200 --> 01:02:31,690
Winchell!
Shh!

1176
01:02:33,080 --> 01:02:36,607
(Whispers) He's everywhere.
I've been working for him since you left.

1177
01:02:37,840 --> 01:02:41,039
You know, some guy
was chasing me with a gun.

1178
01:02:41,040 --> 01:02:42,530
He was shooting at me.

1179
01:02:43,520 --> 01:02:46,319
That didn't have
anything to do with Winchell, did it?

1180
01:02:46,320 --> 01:02:48,079
(Whistles)

1181
01:02:48,080 --> 01:02:51,159
Oh, man! So, why are you doing this?

1182
01:02:51,160 --> 01:02:55,479
I'm not, but if I was, it's because
I think Winchell's gone too far.

1183
01:02:55,480 --> 01:02:58,279
Also, you were always
good to me, North.

1184
01:02:58,280 --> 01:03:01,519
You never picked me last.
You never made me play right field.

1185
01:03:01,520 --> 01:03:04,399
I'll never forget that.
Thanks, Adam.

1186
01:03:04,400 --> 01:03:06,079
(SIREN WAILS)

1187
01:03:06,080 --> 01:03:09,721
Oh, man. Adam, I just
don't feel safe anywhere.

1188
01:03:11,000 --> 01:03:13,879
Adam? Adam?

1189
01:03:13,880 --> 01:03:16,884
(MYSTERIOUS MUSIC)

1190
01:03:28,680 --> 01:03:31,079
Could I have a hot dog with just mustard?

1191
01:03:31,080 --> 01:03:32,570
That'll be $1.

1192
01:03:36,520 --> 01:03:40,639
Out of five. 2-3-4-5.

1193
01:03:40,640 --> 01:03:42,119
There you go.

1194
01:03:42,120 --> 01:03:44,639
(MYSTERIOUS MUSIC)

1195
01:03:44,640 --> 01:03:46,119
Where did you get this?

1196
01:03:46,120 --> 01:03:49,359
Some bum bought a hot dog
about an hour ago. Why?

1197
01:03:49,360 --> 01:03:52,279
No reason.

1198
01:03:52,280 --> 01:03:53,770
(Together) Aah!

1199
01:03:56,200 --> 01:03:57,919
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1200
01:03:57,920 --> 01:03:59,410
(HONKS HORN)

1201
01:04:03,560 --> 01:04:05,369
(HONKS HORN RAPIDLY)

1202
01:04:07,920 --> 01:04:09,410
(GUNSHOT) Aagh!

1203
01:04:12,240 --> 01:04:14,163
(TAXI I '(RES SKID)

1204
01:04:18,680 --> 01:04:20,364
Won't see him no more.

1205
01:05:13,040 --> 01:05:15,611
Watch, watch, watch there, you!

1206
01:05:24,680 --> 01:05:26,159
Excuse me...

1207
01:05:26,160 --> 01:05:28,159
Move it, kid!

1208
01:05:28,160 --> 01:05:29,650
C'mon, move it!

1209
01:05:31,720 --> 01:05:34,485
(LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE)

1210
01:05:35,560 --> 01:05:38,639
Which reminds me of this man
who walked into a bar -

1211
01:05:38,640 --> 01:05:41,559
he sits down next to
